                <p>In Old English, there are also two participles - the past participle ends in <strong>-enge</strong> rather than '-ing',
                and the past particple generally ends in <strong>-ed</strong> or <strong>-od</strong></p> and often has the prefix <strong>ge-</strong>. 
                The past and present participles are used in the formation of verbal constructions, as they are in modern English. For example 
                the verb 'to be' + participle as in '<em>Hit wæs ofer stan getimbrod - It was built on stone</em>' or '<em>Hie ymb þa gatu feohtende wæron - 
                They were always fighting</em>', and the auxilliary + participle 
                construction, as in 'þu hæfst burh getimbrod<em> - You have built a fortress</em>'.</p>
