                <p>In addition to functioning as verbals, participles can also be used as adjectives - in fact, this is one defining feature 
                    of participles. In modern English we can say 'the leaping salmon' - using a present participle as an adjective modifying salmon - and also
                    'the murdered man' - using a past participle as an adjective. In Old English you commonly find participles used as adjectives,
                    such as in the phrase <em>'Se slǣpende man - The sleeping man'</em>. When participles are used as adjectives, they also
                    decline (take endings) like adjectives, and follow the grammar of the noun they modify. So, in the sentence <em>'He gefeng slǣpendne man - 
                    He siezed a sleeping man'</em>, the present participle of '<em>slǣpan - to sleep</em>', <em>slǣpende</em>, takes the accusative, masculine 
                    <strong>-ne</strong></strong> ending of strong adjectives.
                </p>
                <div class="text-center">
                    <div class="grammar-box darkgrey-bg">
                       
                       
                        
